The representations of Siso of the earth and of the water in a new exhibition
"People Swimming in the Swimming Pool" from 2022 is a work of art by Vicente Siso that will be exhibited from January 13th in the "Tierra del Sol" gallery (photograph made available by Vicente Siso)
"Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" - this is the title of the exhibition at the new location of the "Tierra del Sol" gallery in West Hollywood. Siso has been part of the Studio Arts Program since 2012 and is now showing his first solo exhibition. Siso was born in Madrid in 1962 and grew up in Venezuela, Trinidad and Miami. Around the age of twenty, he moved with his family to Southern California.
In numerous series of landscapes, portraits and still lifes with acrylic, pastel, charcoal and watercolor, Siso shows his masterful skill. Inspired by family portraits, his own reference photographs and memories, his colorful compositions show the entire palette of his interests and his knowledge in different media. His tropical and maritime landscapes reflect the places of his past in detailed patterns. People are also integrated to create important connections between culture, memory and nature. Siso titles his artworks in a mixture of Spanish and English - a sign of the celebrated and so important complexities of his life in Los Angeles County. The exhibition "Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" will be inaugurated on Saturday, January 13, with a reception from 6:00 PM to 8:00 PM. The exhibition runs until Sunday, March 3.
Gallery "Tierra del Sol", 7414 Santa Monica Blvd. Further information can be found at tierradelsolgallery.org.
Adapt the old, integrate the new to solve problems
At the district level, we only need to take a look at Sydney's Central Business District: An originally undeveloped landscape was first transformed into a settlement with two-story buildings with a maximum height of 46 meters, and then into a market with today's iconic towers. On a much smaller scale, this can happen in Sydney's centers around the central traffic points. The market center districts must also develop further, with a tendency towards more affordable living space with buildings that are further overgrown by plants in the main areas. Naturally, this newly created living space must convince in terms of design, and the plants, the landscape design and the parks must be integrated into the existing essential infrastructure.
Our planning system must adapt immediately, so that the responsible persons in the district councils of the market centers, who are rather critical of changes, do not alone determine the future concept of their neighborhoods. One possibility would be to install an independent decision-making body that is committed to high-quality concepts that end up on the rooftops of the buildings and provide space for families, large balconies and communal courtyards - and are also visually appealing. This could be a lesson for the current NSW government architect, based on a carefully developed ordinance.
Over the last 10 years, our lives have been transformed by technology. Many people work from home, and Sydney has gained an impressive network of metros and urban railways. Online shopping has changed the way we shop, and thanks to smartphones, friends and families can stay in better contact. Precisely such adaptations from one system to another are also possible in our construction environment. In this context, the focus of planning should be on adaptive reuse and not on a favored conversion of the old.
Chris Johnson was the NSW Government Architect from 1995 to 2005 and Executive Director of the NSW Planning Division from 2005 to 2009. From 2011 to 2019, he was CEO of the Urban Taskforce Australia.
A final intervention for equality between women and men
Last year, the World Economic Forum predicted that it would take five generations to achieve gender equality in every country. Now the World Bank wants to significantly shorten this timeframe.
The international financial institution is introducing a strategy to significantly promote the economic opportunities of girls and women by 2030. The plan focuses on the goal of improving inclusion and resilience by providing access to finance, technical innovation, and changes in public directives and laws.
The recent study has shown that although social norms and ways of speaking can change, and that the integration of men and boys, for example, can help support gender equality, this cannot be read in a draft consultation of the plan. "Positive results in connection with equality can be accelerated and scaled if one better understands... how social norms and attitudes influence expectations, priorities, and daily practices."
Changes in thinking are more difficult to quantify compared to bank loans for women on the ground or school announcements for girls. However, there are numerous indications that show that the integration of women can move mountains. In Iran, for example, women have become the greatest threat to the Islamic government in 40 years: they have refused to observe the laws that force them to cover their heads. In some of the 130 countries with minimum quotas for the representation of women in government, for example in India, male resistance against women's right to vote and political activity has been reduced.
In some rural communities in Africa, civil society organizations are replacing an extremely harmful initiation rite with health education. One of these programs helped Kamanda Timayio, traditional chief of the Maasai Maparasha community in Kenya, to change his attitude towards female genital mutilation. He told Le Monde that he had "overcome his ignorance" and that he would abandon the practice.
The World Bank cites further examples. From 1970 to 2022, the literacy rate of women in Bangladesh quadrupled and the participation of women in the labor market doubled. The country's gross domestic product tripled. The change developed its own dynamic. The employment of women as paid health supervisors and workers in the communities themselves created trust "and made the mobility and professional activity of women more accepted in society."
The bank's plan focuses on the norms and institutions in which the generational change has perhaps not yet taken place. In Rwanda, it took more than two decades for the country to establish itself as a model for agricultural reforms and to promote the economic empowerment of women. "It helps no one if women are kept down," said Rwandan President Paul Kagame when he spoke in favor of agricultural reform in 2015. "We must change ways of thinking, not just laws."
The World Bank hopes to be able to spread this message.
The farmers and the locomotive drivers of Germany are causing fear among the German entrepreneurs.
In Germany, where employees and employers usually run many companies together, there are unusually large strikes. A big wave of strikes has hardly ever happened. But currently, the "land of compromise" has to face a wave of strikes, during which not only angry farmers block the roads with tractors for eight days, but also railway workers go on strike for three days. And as if that weren't enough, doctors have now also threatened to strike, and indeed, between Christmas and New Year, doctors' practices have closed their doors. This "mob with pitchforks", as some call it, will put the harmonious relations in Germany to the test at the beginning of the year.
The protests appear to have been triggered by the government's decision to cut diesel subsidies for agriculture and reduce tax breaks for agricultural vehicles. These measures have exceeded the limits for farmers. They have also mobilized other angry workers who are already suffering under the burden of inflation, economic recession, and the austerity measures imposed by the government. On January 9, freight and passenger train drivers of Deutsche Bahn began a strike to protest against working hours and pay.
To reduce tensions with the farmers, the government has declared itself ready to progressively reduce diesel subsidies over the next three years. The exemption from tax on agricultural vehicles should also be maintained. The farmers have rejected the concessions, deeming them insufficient. On January 4, Economy Minister Robert Habeck had to leave a ferry after his return from vacation with his family, but a group of aggressive protesters tried to prevent that. If the train drivers also prove to be unimpressed, this could become expensive for the German economy, estimates the IW Economic Research Institute in Cologne. The strike by the railways could cost the economy 100 million euros a day if production had to be interrupted. The automotive, chemical, and steel industries, the largest economic sectors in Germany, are particularly dependent on freight transport by rail.
The atmosphere among the workers is becoming increasingly tense. "They are running around with fantasies of revolution," Habeck warned. The far-right party Alternative for Germany is doing its best to fuel these protests. In Dresden, the Freie Sachsen, another far-right party, infiltrated the farmers' protests and called for "inciting the masses."
Thomas Puls from the IW in Cologne fears that the protests could damage Germany's reputation as an economic hub. Local entrepreneurs are already worried that there could be a German version of the yellow vest protests like in France in 2018, which ended with demonstrators setting cars on fire on the Champs-Élysées and the police intervening with tear gas. Jochen Kopelke, head of the police union, warned in an interview with the Tagesspiegel: "The farmers' protests are probably just the beginning of an enormous wave of protests that will reach us this year." Germany was the only one of the major economic regions to shrink in 2023, and the year ended on a particularly bitter note: an unexpected drop in economic confidence in December. The current year could become even more difficult.
The farmers in villages where wine producers are located are exempt from the regulations regarding waste reduction.
In the context of the EU debates on regulations to reduce waste, breweries argue that the exceptions granted to winemakers in connection with reuse targets and deposit refund systems disadvantage them. However, one of the officials of the European Wine Industry Association believes that brewers "should mind their own business."
European breweries warn that it is a bad and illegal move to grant exceptions from reuse targets to deposit-return systems for wine, but not for beer. Meanwhile, legislators are in the final round of discussions about a new law that should turn the tide on the growing mountains of packaging waste in the EU.
The environment ministers agreed before Christmas on a negotiating mandate from the Council of Europe regarding the proposal for a regulation to regulate packaging and packaging waste, thus clearing the way for the long-standing political discussions with the European Parliament, which have already begun at a technical level.
"Our position is clear," the umbrella association of European brewers, Brewers of Europe, wrote to the delegates of the European Parliament and the government negotiators (January 10). "If the goals and regulations of the packaging and packaging waste regulation apply to beer, there is a legal obligation to apply them to all categories of alcoholic beverages."
At their supreme meeting on December 18, the ministers concluded an exception for winegrowers from the obligation to offer 10% of products in reusable containers in a reusable or refillable system until the end of the decade. By 2040, this share should increase to 40%. This exception should also apply to the claim to exclude wine from deposit refund systems. This claim is also supported by the European Parliament and should be introduced into the proposal by 2029.
Even if the Czech minister and the Belgian minister immediately expressed their reservations about the unequal treatment of the brewers at the supreme meeting of December 18, they gave their consent. Belgium, which is now in turn to lead the EU presidency and should therefore remain neutral in the negotiations between the governments, hopes that a deal with the parliament will be reached by the beginning of March.
Ignacio Sánchez Recarte, Secretary General of the European Wine Industry Association, the Comité Européen des Entreprises Vin, which represents over 7,000 winegrowers across Europe, does not share the brewers' reservations. He told Euronews that a market dominated by multinational brewery conglomerates should not be compared with an industry that is almost entirely made up of small national producers.
More than 99% of the domestic beer industry consists of very small to medium-sized companies, said Sánchez Reacarte. He also questioned the validity of the legal arguments put forward by the breweries. According to him, his organization is committed to presenting "relevant and adequate" information to decision-makers for their own industry.
It is not my role to evaluate whether the beer industry should open this or that window, because that depends on the specific characteristics of its own industry, Sánchez Recarte declared. "Therefore, brewers should mind their own business and concentrate on their own obligations."
Brewers of Europe shared a short legal analysis with Euronews that the association sent to the European Commission last year. In it, they argue that beer and wine are competing products "only partially interchangeable with each other," and that rules favoring one industry over another distort the market.
Simon Spillane, the lobby's chief operating officer, said that brewers already occupy "a leadership position" when it comes to sustainable packaging. He points to the example of beer bottles, which can be reused around 165 times before they are recycled after 30 years. They already support reuse and recycling systems introduced in many countries.
"Therefore, we advocate for an ambitious regulation concerning packaging and packaging waste. But we also need equal conditions in the packaging legislation that promises to treat beer and other alcoholic beverages according to the same rules. Every industry should contribute in the same way to achieve the goals and support the collection systems," said Spillane. "Any other approach means a competitive disadvantage for brewers."
The Biden administration releases economic criminals
Tim Whitehouse, the former lawyer for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and managing director of Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, praised the Biden administration's recent improvements in enforcing environmental law, but also conceded that such efforts face much resistance. "It takes years of reliable funding and political support to develop a good enforcement program," he told me. "Congressional instability not only demoralizes EPA staff, but also undermines their ability to think strategically and long-term."
The EPA's problems are not identical, but comparable to those of the Ministry of Justice. Its Environment and Natural Resources Division (ENRD) deals with environmental crime. Uhlmann, the Deputy Minister for Law Enforcement, was, before joining the EPA, from 1990 to 2007 head of the environmental crime section. The EPA sends its most serious civil and criminal cases to the ENRD, which, as a rather poorly funded authority, often relies on others to decide which battles to fight. In the 2022 fiscal year, the EPA transmitted fewer cases (88) to the Ministry of Justice than in 2000 and completed the fewest civil proceedings since that date. As mentioned in the environmental integrity project, the EPA completed an average of 94 civil proceedings even under Trump and transmitted 106 cases per year to the Minister of Justice.
The general procedure of the Ministry of Justice in connection with economic crime cases was examined in detail by the members. Observers praised some steps introduced by the ministry under Merrick Garland as Minister of Justice - such as the creation of a database for environmental crime. However, Biden's Ministry of Justice has also firmly lowered its sights on the main witness programs that promise companies to delay or avoid criminal prosecution and encourage them to denounce individual employees to avoid more comprehensive accusations. Kenneth Polite Jr., the former Deputy Assistant Attorney General in the Criminal Division, has revised the division's enforcement guidelines for companies to limit prosecutions.
The debate about the shutdown fuels the Republicans' conflict
The opponents of spending, the conservatives in the House of Representatives, have opposed the party leaders and have sunk a series of votes. Thus, they have protested against the most recent spending agreement of President Mike Johnson with the leaders of the Democrats, which in their opinion does not foresee sufficient budget reductions.
Even now, the Republican from Louisiana can get out of the way on the issue, but the final date for the deliberation of four of the twelve annual budgets is January 19. Johnson has publicly declared that he will not support a transitional law called "Continuing Resolution" to extend the deadline for those four draft laws until the deadline for the remaining eight on February 2.
In view of the fact that there are only nine days left until this term ends, the leader of the Republican faction in the Senate, Mitch McConnell, announced that Congress should deliberate a "Continuing Resolution" to keep the government running. This means that the Speaker of the House could soon break a promise, with which he primarily wanted to appease the right wing of his party. Such a maneuver could cause a lively ideological debate about the role of Republicans in questions of expenditure reduction, which could lead to a partial government shutdown or the dismissal of Johnson from office.
The congressman Matt Rosendale from Montana declared to Newsweek: "I have clearly said that 'Continuing Resolutions' are not the appropriate way to finance our government, since the budget law of 1974 foresees the approval of 12 credit projects. We have had more than enough time, and if the leaders do not assign the committees to do their work and let the members of Congress vote, then that is the reason for the failure."
The Speaker of the House of Representatives, Mike Johnson, at the U.S. Capitol on December 12, 2023 in Washington, D.C. Johnson faces a rebellious Republican faction that is unable to reach an agreement on the ceiling of budget expenditures. Photograph: Kevin Dietsch/Getty Images
Rosendale, who is part of the far-right Freedom Caucus group, was one of those who caused the mid-term vote to fail. He and the total sum of Johnson's proposal consider it far too insufficient to reduce the national debt of 34 trillion dollars.
Rosendale was also one of the 71 Republicans who opposed the Fiscal Responsibility Act: the law on fiscal responsibility, negotiated between the Democrats and the former speaker Kevin McCarthy, which determines the basic conditions for Johnson's recent negotiations with the leader of the Democrats in the Senate, Charles Schumer.
While Johnson praised the merits of his agreement, which promised to save expenses of about 16 billion dollars, the Freedom Caucus meant that he could have achieved more. The moderate Republicans who supported McCarthy's agreement consider that stance unrealistic and contrary to the Republicans' goal of forcing Congress to approve the twelve bills individually and not to combine them with a so-called omnibus procedure in a single vote as in recent years.
"Again, the same idiotic behavior from some," Republican Congressman Mike Lawler of New York declared to Newsweek. "Since there will be no omnibus procedure, every bill must be deliberated and negotiated separately. It seems we will probably need more time for that. And I do not support a shutdown - I also have no problem with a short-term 'Continuing Resolution' so that this process can be brought to a good end."
It was the first time since 1996 that Congress approved all twelve bills separately. According to Lawler, it was worth approving the four delayed bills to ensure an orderly process. If Congress fails to approve the twelve bills by December, the Fiscal Responsibility Act will apply a one percent budget cut to defense and non-defense spending.
Congressman Thomas Massie of Kentucky - probably one of the most ardent opponents of Republican Party spending - did not join those who protested against the vote. He did, however, declare that a 'Continuing Resolution' for one year with the consequence of a one percent reduction in spending was the most practical way to ensure the functioning of the government and at the same time end the dispute with the risk.
The most responsible way to achieve spending cuts is for Massie to approve all draft laws. Many Republicans do not want to risk a shutdown and thus a one percent reduction in defense spending. The urgency with which the draft laws must be approved could contribute to a sufficient number of Republicans aligning with the Democrats to extend the deadline for the first four draft laws and reach an agreement on the funding of government work, even if that would mean that Johnson could face problems with some right-wing hardliners.
"It [the one percent reduction] should be a motivation by way of pressure to approve the twelve draft laws separately," Massie declared to Newsweek. "Then we could first approve a 'Continuing Resolution', then exchange our arguments, and when we are then facing that small obstacle, hopefully everyone will have reasons to act reasonably. That's how I would do it."
The supervisory authority approves new Bitcoin ETFs - a milestone for cryptocurrencies
The US stock exchange supervisory authority Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) has recently given the green light for exchange-traded funds (ETFs) in bitcoins. This is a step long awaited by supporters of digital currencies and criticized by financial observers skeptical of the crypto industry.
The authority has approved ten ETFs that invest in bitcoins, among other funds from industry giants like Blackrock and Fidelity, but also from smaller financial companies.
"The fact that we approved today the quotation on the stock exchange and the trading of certain bitcoin products traded on the stock exchange does not mean that we ban or approve bitcoins," SEC chief Gary Gensler declared in a statement. "Investors should still be cautious given the numerous risks associated with bitcoins and products with a value linked to cryptocurrencies."
He added that the approval of bitcoin funds does not mean that funds or other products traded on the stock exchange (ETPs), which are based on other currencies or digital asset values, will be approved by the SEC.
"What is important is the fact that today's approval is limited to ETPs that contain a specific product not linked to currencies, namely Bitcoin. With this, we are in no way signaling a readiness to allow approval standards for crypto-assets. The approval also says nothing about the SEC's stance regarding the status of other crypto-assets within the framework of American currency laws or regarding the non-compliance of certain participants in the crypto-asset market with currency laws," Gensler said.
Over the years, applications for similar funds have been rejected by the SEC. Last year, the US Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled that the SEC's refusal to approve Grayscale's application to convert a derivatives fund was illegal. This was to be converted into a fund that would invest directly in bitcoin. The court described the SEC's stance as "unmotivated and arbitrary".
Gensler declared that he sees - in view of these circumstances and of those that have been presented in more detail to the approval decision - the opinion that the most practical way for the future is to approve the listing and trading of these bitcoin-spot-ETP shares.
The approval, awaited with great tension, has been welcomed as a milestone for digital currencies. According to its adherents, it increases access to investments in bitcoins and could lead to a wider acceptance of cryptocurrencies as a serious financial investment. The price of bitcoin has exploded in recent months from around 25,000 dollars in September to over 45,000 dollars. This is partly attributable to the fact that many bitcoin investors believe that ETFs will create a greater demand for this asset.
The opponents of the decision sharply criticised the SEC last night.
Dennis M. Kelleher, co-founder, president and CEO of Better Markets, said that the approval was a "historic mistake. It not only frees cryptocurrency leaders to defraud millions of investors and pensioners, but also probably undermines the stability of financial markets."
Kelleher further stated that "the crypto industry, seemingly without laws, has reached its lowest point based on a mass of arrests, convictions, insolvencies, lawsuits, scandals, massive layoffs, and millions of victims among investors and clients. Who would have thought that the SEC would support it by approving a proven and reliable form of investment. Thus, the SEC enables the mass commercialization of a financial product without value, volatile and dangerous to American citizens."
30% more complaints about the use of the Russian language in Ukraine - RT Russia and the former Soviet Union
To disinfect the earth, the authorities order the population to stay home.
The number of complaints submitted to the Ukrainian authorities about people speaking Russian increased by 30% last year. The authorities in Kyiv actively encourage the population to report such cases, supposedly to "protect" the country from Russian influence.
According to the indications of the office of the commissioner for the protection of the national language, 3,692 violations against the language law were reported in 2023. Kyiv, Kharkiv and Odesa are "still at the top when it comes to the number of violations. One of the priorities of the communal authorities should be to strictly monitor that the language rights of citizens are respected in all sectors of public life," said Taras Kremen, the public mediator for languages in Ukraine.
The Kremlin has also confirmed that a fine of 3,400 Hryvnia (89 dollars) was imposed on a taxi driver from Kyiv who addressed his customers in Russian. The public mediator drew the public's attention to the fact that there is "a detailed algorithm of actions in case the right to receive information or services in the state language is violated." He urged the population to immediately file a complaint on the mediator's website in such cases.
In 2019, Ukraine approved a law that obliges the use of the Ukrainian language in all sectors of public life, including government, trade, science, education, and the media. Fines are threatened in case of violations. Since the beginning of the military conflict with Russia in 2022, Ukraine has been conducting a total de-Russification campaign, which, according to parliamentarians, is necessary to protect itself against Russian influence. Local authorities have completely banned works of art, performances, books, films, songs, and instruction in the Russian language in schools and universities, and have recommended that schoolchildren speak Ukrainian with each other even during breaks.
Last August, a young musician was briefly arrested and forced to apologize via video message, after he had performed songs by the Soviet singer Viktor Tsoi on the streets of Lviv. The dismissal of several teachers who had spoken Russian with their students also caused a public outcry.
The secretary of the National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine, Oleksiy Danilov, had previously declared that the Russian language should disappear from Ukrainian territory, because it is "an element of enemy propaganda and a brainwashing of the population".
As long as the Moscow government violates such laws, the rights of the Russian population, which comprises about half of the inhabitants of Ukraine, are violated. The spokeswoman of the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Maria Zakharova, declared in February that Kiev's "discriminatory campaign" against the language is becoming increasingly "revolting". In a survey conducted last September by the International Institute for Sociology in Kiev, 45% of the respondents indicated that linguistic discrimination is the most frequent type of prejudice in Ukraine.
The Celest and the rainbow of corruption favor "from the small to the good freeware game, to the big commercial game, even with a detailed graphics", because in the original and the double dash a power-up without context in a treasure chest and in this commercial game I had to pay for it.
In general, I liked the interaction of the two genres very much. The advantage of short stories is that one can "jump to the good part". That can be more interesting and satisfying. The advantage of long stories is that one can give the action elements a much greater emotional weight. However, something doesn't happen immediately, sometimes one gets more.
The highlight of Celeste, the commercial game, and actually the Pico-8 game, is that it is built with a mechanical and narrative construction of several hours, so that it becomes much, much harder. Celeste is so proud of its parent game that it always adds references like the monument, the progression of "2000 M... 2500 M...", the power-up, the flag above. One can play the original game directly on the start monitor!
Celest is neither "the good version" nor "the rented version" of Pico-8, it is just another version of the same main story. For someone who likes short stories as well as long stories, it is really interesting and great to see how the collection has been made so evident.
It was possible to develop between the two versions yet another medium-length variant that tells the same story in an extended and expressive way, but with a shorter duration and less narrative production values. I believe that this would have been my preferred variant, as an arc of emotional tension. Instead, this and the main arc of tension make individual players only a small part of it. Above all, it would be a great playground for the most popular platform physics in the world, which in my opinion is still in order.
