I only needed a full anaesthetic once for an operation. This was a "small" neurosurgical intervention to give my brain more space, because I was born with a disease that caused symptoms after I had children (Chiari malformation). The moment I woke up, I never forgot it and it always comes back to me a little when I watch medical shows, especially those with a neurosurgeon. I've had the hospital playlist on my list for a long time and it suits me very well at the moment. #kdrama
My surgeon really thinks of everything. He called me the day before because it was going to be slippery, and when the care team was taking care of me the moment I woke up from the anaesthesia in the recovery room, my surgeon realised that I had opened my eyes and the bandage was in front of my eyes. I mean all that, plus still doing the operation. But it was still confusing. That was one of the things that gave me the biggest scare. I slept and yes, it passed.
I had my period, but I had to take off my underwear. That's why they gave me that net underwear that you wear after giving birth. But in the operating room, you have to take off everything completely and you are covered with a sheet. At some point, before I woke up, a kind nurse changed my underwear. Other than during the births, where I was awake and received help, even as a baby, no one had ever done anything so private for me. That was also the only time in the intensive care unit. I had to go to the intensive care unit as a preventive measure, because of the type of operation.
I had to rest a lot after my operation, then I wanted to watch seasons 1-3 of Grey's Anatomy. It helped me that McDreamy was a neurosurgeon. I paid attention to how the patient was positioned, to be able to imagine what happened to me. Since my operation in 2018, Hospital Playlist has shown more about neurosurgery than any other medical show I've seen since Grey's. How beautiful that there is art and entertainment to give meaning to our lives.
@user32 Thanks to Hospital Playlist I would know how to transplant a liver.
@user33 Wow!
I think a lot that the millennials were the last generation that knew how to build relationships with artists, without anyone expecting them to be critical in any way.
We grew up in a time of media with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We have been able to let ourselves be fascinated by things without having to share where they come from, because at that time it was not so easy to find that out.
We didn't have to question the power we had. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
Therefore we have such a strong need for nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still running, my friends and I used to order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
That was completely different from streaming, where 12 episodes appear at the same time and everyone watches when they feel like it and puts "spoiler warnings" at the beginning of their social media posts or discusses it in closed groups.
Unconsciously we belong to that universal community that knew how to do everything.
Why do so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or films like "Anchorman" with so many references in one line that would be memes today?
We have repeated these verses and have noticed that many already understand them.
Today I don't want to start from the fact that everyone understands something, even if it spreads virally.
He gives a lot, a lot, and he gives no possibility to systematize that. If we ever get out of this mess again?
We are caught in a circle of devils that forces us to always discover new content, but to realize that the artist is on the money and a hypocrite.
Therefore we are forced to keep our nostalgia alive and at the same time accept that the people who created the works that fill us also made great mistakes.
We get involved in parasocial relationships with great attention.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without standing on one's own feet and without helping each other.
As we have lost our collective consciousness in connection with the media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical sharing.
There are still those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to then be shocked when the person falls.
We are in a phase of profound change and I am curious where we will end up.
Inclusion in society should be the standard.
