It's an absolute niche problem, but if you want to build/personalize robot figures, it really gets on your nerves that you HAVE to build something that is made for war and for killing.
Like the years nothing. Then came the Bionicles. These were actually adventurers/heroes with very elemental powers and with different personalities and hobbies and so on, but before and after there was much more of that like Warhammer, Gundam, Battletech, where everything is conceived to be a weapon and is staged in the accompanying media in a completely unnecessary way.
Clearly, those other sources say that "war is bad", but then they sell killing machines as merchandising figures. What can we do?
The separation was more like separating between them, appearing to that fictitious intent, as one also does in the real world with tanks and jets, but my brain had DIFFICULTY with that.
Because the figures look cool, and I like more how they are built and how their design reflects certain characteristic traits, but then for every set it's: "Here, here's your lightsaber and your (at least one) pistol!"
This probably has a lot to do with the fact that toys for boys almost always have something to do with violence, like GI Joe and Transformers, but let's be honest, we are in the current year.
