A self-confessed anarchist, for whom it is absolutely essential to keep his identity secret, gives his DNA to a biotechnology company to receive a dubious overview of his "ancestry". What could possibly go wrong?
My wife takes this as a starting point. Without going into too much depth here, she believes that some of her ancestors are actually not her ancestors. I want to support her and see the effect of a genetic drift based on a small control experiment. We know a lot about our family.
Strength gives its own eye to the other in my family that was untrustworthy, but if one looks at my family risks, for the most part poor, in all affairs probably succeeded in mostly homogeneous communities, in small markets and ethnic ghettos, lol.
My aunt left her husband for his brother, and I have a stepbrother from the other side of the family who left his wife for her aunt. My family travels a lot, but not really far.
Now to my bad wife, because my "extraction" went much faster than expected. I'm doing badly, her genome must not be allowed to beg like that.
The results are here and - drum roll - they correspond perfectly to my family history. 89.9% British and Irish, mostly concentrated in the Scottish Borders region, eastern Ireland, Wales and Cornwall. There isn't much Breton, perhaps because it's so close to Cornwall that it can't be distinguished from me, nor that my Breton family doesn't come from there.
