You rarely have time to relax as an academic, but in those moments when you're not at the desk, you have the best ideas. 💭
Trying harder to publish more does not always lead to better results. One must not forget to relax if one wants to become a better scientist.
Thus I recharge my batteries again.
It affects both hemispheres of the brain. 🧠
When I don't do anything, I generally use the analytical part of my brain. But if I use the creative part (e.g., to play guitar, paint, etc.) and also the analytical part of my brain, I have the impression of having increased my mental capacities. This way I improve in both areas.
Train the muscles, not the head. 💪
Sport is not just something for future triathletes or people who want to look better. Sport also improves the quality of life. Thoughts, mood, productivity: everything is connected. Taking a break once in a while and stepping away from the desk makes the time spent at the desk much more productive.
Permission to relax. 📺
Recharging your batteries doesn't necessarily mean you have to learn new things. A good film or a good book can have the same effect as creative work or physical activity. The important thing is to become aware that it's okay to relax and do nothing. There's no room for feelings of guilt!
I've heard that these things help me to relax. But there are still many others. What does one do not to lose enthusiasm for science and not to get a burnout? 🤔
