AT HOME
The development of humanity continues in a context. Even in difficult times, we develop and adapt. Markets and prosperity are still great, and technological progress is advancing. With the recent discovery of Ignniat, humanity has been catapulted into unimaginable heights; but something much greater still awaits us. This newly acquired knowledge may be valued as a divine intervention, and the Gods will rejoice at our presence in heaven. The Karascene company has already intensively examined Ignniat and estimates the potential of this mineral as very high. And don't worry: according to the examinations, no side effects or problems with decomposing Ignniat are to be expected. This mineral is destined for greater purposes.
January 14, 10:26 PM.
One click. The same stream repeats in a content: the day the world was devastated. My father always sighed when he saw that I couldn't turn my eyes away. My stomach churned as I saw his worried face. I always feel bad when this stream comes, because it awakens so many memories in me, but not very good ones. With a sigh, I try to move on to other thoughts. I always try to cheer him up and chase away his bad mood by at least making a small joke, but today I am tired.
I slowly open the door and call to my father: "I'm going out for a bit, it's getting dark and cold." No answer. What else. Most of the time he hears me, he'll come and close it himself. I close the door almost completely and sigh once more, when it closes completely in the evening. I had almost forgotten to put my hand on the cold metal scanner to close the door. If there was anything special about that apartment, it was the equipment with modern technology, which was the case in most buildings. Yes, to be honest, no other technology was needed.
On that cold and rainy night, I took my exploratory walk, planned by Paltricus - a privilege reserved for those who had escaped or had unexpected luck. The night was illuminated by twinkling stars that were already many millennia old. It must be lonely in the universe. Paltricus was a beautiful market, but one felt more like in a cloister and not like in a luxurious dwelling. The market was full of apartments, houses, and other buildings; most had several hundred floors, thanks to Ignniat. This mineral had proven to be a true fortune for technology and architecture and had enlarged our living base. However, little is published about this mineral, especially because it is kept strictly secret.
To get rid of my dark thoughts, I set off for a coffee in my favourite local. It is avoided by most people because it is rumoured that a plague has been there. That's what those who have been infected with the virus are called. That didn't bother me - I've had enough bad luck in my life - and the owner is a great guy. Who would also refuse a free coffee in exchange for a late-night chat?
As I entered, my discomfort was chased away by a strong smell of fresh coffee and pastries in my nose. Anton, the owner of the place, was behind the counter as always. The place was practically empty, with the exception of one person in the back. After the long walk, I approached the bar, dead tired, and let myself fall onto one of the stools. I saw Anton and he brought me the usual. "Hello Lilith, a long night?", and his calm voice resonated through the depths of my brain. "Something like that," I replied very weakly and became more and more tired by the second.
To chase away my tiredness, I often drank a cup of coffee before me. "Is business still going badly since that story with the pastries...?" I whispered secretly so as not to scare away the last guests in Anton's place. He nodded while he wiped a glass with a cloth. This place is actually a bar, but I didn't come here to drink a drink. Behind me, there was a murmur, but the conversation between Anton and me was rather short this evening. With a short farewell sign and with a little more energy than before, I left the place.
It was usually not the best idea to walk the dark streets late at night. But it was still better than staying in that stuffy apartment and listening to the neighbors having sex. They heard that more often than their own music. With a short sigh, I again directed my gaze to the road in front of me. I'm probably going to Al's pawn shop to pass the time by looking to see if there's any interesting old stuff around. When I hear footsteps right behind me, I regret my decision. Maybe I'm making too many worries, but in this neighborhood, you only move when you want to be robbed or beaten up. The neighborhood is known for its mafia and gang crime.
And isn't that nice? Just half of the people and still ahead of us to make sure we don't harm each other. I went faster, the pawn shop was just around the corner and I was safe there too. When I stood in front of an illuminated sign with the inscription "Alborn's pawn shop", a quick glance over the counter confirmed that I was no longer being pursued. With a calmer step, I entered the shop. It was a bit off the road, because Alborn often took in mutants who lived without permission in Paltricus. It was dark in the shop and Al was curiously not around either. No fugitives. Nothing. Something wasn't right here.
Carefully I slipped into the back part of the station, where one heard a murmur and hushed conversations behind a metal grate that one could remove with a few hand movements. I slipped into the ventilation shaft - at the moment the simplest and safest method. As I push through, I hear a conversation between two men, strangely dressed. Then I see Al, in chains. It was clear that they would pay him back one day.
I really liked Alborn, but that was a number too big for me. And anyway, I don't always have to stick my nose into other people's business, especially not when they're having trouble with the market authorities. Nevertheless, I couldn't do otherwise. With a sigh, I carefully lifted the boy from under me out of his embrace and slipped down into the silent room. "Psst, Al. Al!" I whispered, and when he didn't answer, I raised my voice. "Lilith? What are you doing here? You have to go, otherwise he'll catch you too."
"What you told me...", I said to myself secretly. While we were trying to free the chains around his arm, we heard voices approaching and the silent steps became louder and louder. "Quick! Get back into the cave and disappear. Don't come back under any circumstances. If we make it, then meet me in that market." He quickly nodded and the panic in his eyes didn't help to calm me down. I followed his advice. I couldn't stay any longer. Damn it, Al! After leaving the ventilation shaft, I ran away. It hurt to lose such a loyal friend. Were they going to take him to the other... market? So many things went through my head. I was so angry, but also sad. I was intensively dealing with the external markets and with the capital of the infected. It was called Alcatraz, just like the prison. The name fit well with what I had read. Not to mention that the unmentionables had interrupted all connections with the lands of the infected. A tragedy.
A noisy silence accompanied me on my way home. The thoughts in my head tumbled and almost tore me apart, because I hadn't been able to help Al. When I finally arrived home after that terrible walk, I was on the verge of crying, and the sounds of the thunder, which came from the floor above me, could instill fear and anxiety in anyone. My father was already asleep on the sofa. A rerun of a film from 10-12 years ago was just playing. With a sigh, I went quietly into my room. I just let myself fall onto the bed. I could barely keep my eyes open and almost immediately fell asleep.
EXPLOSION
January 19, 2:34 PM.
Time flew by. A couple of days ago Alborn had been transported away. I didn't know where. But that they had taken him somewhere. The men's clothing had become unfamiliar to me, but I simply couldn't remember where. With a sigh, I placed my hands on the system in front of me that glowed red and violet - as if it were a trifle to me. I doubt they've secured it additionally... But it's better not to. But naturally, I pushed my moral reservations aside. My finger wandered tirelessly over the keyboard and called up various monitors. Devilishly, I'm good. I've been very well-known on certain websites, someone there called me "SPIERT". A name that one remembers well. But I admit that I use the name SPI3RT on every website, but I like the idea that I got it from others.
I loaded the surveillance camera footage onto my mobile phone and watched everyone intently. Nut. As if they had never been there. That makes no sense. The cameras are well secured, even against remote access. How...? DAMN. I was so angry that I stood up to chase the thoughts out of my head. I went to the door and grabbed my keys. "I'll be back soon, Dad." Silence. That's normal, he never answered anyway. He was probably busy with something more important than me again.
When I left the apartment, I felt a strange emptiness. I ignored it and was forced to go to the train station to do some research. My legs, however, carried me to Anton's small bar. It was very quiet there and I urgently needed someone to chat with. Who would have been more suitable than a bartender who was used to me?
It was unusually full, very full of people I had never seen before. Anton usually worked alone and was certainly very stressed because of the many people. "I'd like a coffee." I deliberately spoke in a low tone to annoy him a little. He turned briefly and I had to laugh secretly when I saw the expression on his face. "Damn Lilith, don't look at me like that...", he said secretly, with a tired voice. "You look like you have a lot to do... Should I help you? There's a lot going on here." I really didn't feel like serving those strangers, but I felt sorry for Anton, because he had to serve that crowd all alone. "Would you do that? You'll get your money later...", he grumbled and looked at me with his dog eyes. Advanced war tactics...
After I had exchanged my clothes for a work uniform, I helped Anton at the bar. Despite his constant attempts to flirt and attract my attention, which, to be honest, didn't even bother me, the work went smoothly. I came to chat with Anton after the shift. I have to get Al out of my head, even though I know I'll do further investigations in his pawn shop after that shift at the bar, but anyway...
Flames in routes out of Thassalin's throat, when the gigantic Thraki had set fire to a piece of specific gold and then circled over to discover movements. Curiously, the red giant was placed behind him when he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"What's that, Tenuk, you've already been in a Thracian once!"
"When I fly myself, it's something completely different than always being caught in the air by a pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel was obviously not of the same opinion as Nyssi. He looked less black than usual and his claws were dug so deeply into Thassalin's back that Thraki was bleeding. Thassalin, however, seemed to enjoy it. Nevertheless, he realized that he had scared his new friends, and he retreated into a clearing.
"I'm just standing, but I'm going to do something. I have to take care of that!"
"But did you have to drag us along with you?" the Tenuk grumbled, as he slid down Thassalin's back and scurried down her tail. "We've already lost the Retvik! We've already lost our great and fierce warrior! How can he possibly follow us?"
"He'll surely try to get something into his head...", Nyssi grumbled. "Retvik isn't the smartest, but he's not stupid."
"That's good, but can Retvik go by car?
The Nyssi nodded and turned towards the Tenuk. "Of course he can go by car."
"Have you ever seen Reto go by vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I've never seen him go in a car as elegant as Kayel's. And besides, he only started going to work by car because you always go by vehicle. He has his bike."
They are interrupted by a loud laugh. Thassalin always seemed to enjoy himself enormously, but no one knew what he was laughing at. It didn't take long until Thassalin calmed down.
"I stood there once, when I saw your gigantic friend in armor without a helmet and a child's mini-bike. That was to laugh until you burst! I wish I had some kind of telepathy. A wild imagination! One that I can't park!"
Kayel sighed, because he could imagine what was going through Thassalin's head. "Yes, you are right. But what did you do and why did he fly away so suddenly?"
The Thassalin roared, rose and disappeared. When he returned after a short time, he threw something dead at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare dragon-like creature, golden white. But its head was gone. "ANOTHER DEAD. I HATE ITS SCREAM. I FREEZE ITS BLOOD. SOMETHING IS HUNTING ME TO PROTECT AND TO HUNT. AS THE YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY CLOSE."
The gigantic Thraki was completely torn apart. Nyssi and Kayel also stood still and directed their gaze to a wide clearing. Something big and black stared at them, snorting. Whatever it was, it spread two pairs of gigantic wings and flew straight towards Thassalin without being interested in the three smaller beings between them. Kayel and Tenuk had just been able to get to safety, but Nyssi was dragged along and was almost catapulted onto Thassalin.
The Thassalin reacted to that attack by grabbing the Nyssi and hitting her with his cunning and incredibly long tail on her back, before throwing her into the air. The black creature with double wings pursued them with great speed.
Kayel slapped his tongue while taking his bow off his back and opening a pouch containing an ammunition belt. He wrapped the belt around the bow, but soon realized that Nyssi, Thraki, and the monster were no longer visible.
"Hey, Tenuk, could you imagine something that can fly?", asked Kayel.
"Do you want to prosecute them?"
"Yes, naturally!"
"But... one of them is a gigantic monster!"
"Yes, and then? I'm here with a shotgun and could shoot immediately. But I would naturally have to see him to be able to hit him."
The Tenuk stretched, then it took a step back to have more space. With a loud, powerful breath, the Tenuk's body lengthened, its skin turned into scales and its arms into wings. It quickly turned into a normal, light blue Thraki, but its eyes remained red.
"Saragata is a sieve."
As a Thracian of normal appearance, the Tenuk now had real scales along its back. And from its back had also grown two spines, which was practical, so the Kayel could sit on them. I went a little further until the Tenuk was about to leave, but once it was in the air, it quickly oriented itself and began to pursue.
The Tuenuk and the Kayel quickly realized that they were not alone. A second dark and shadowy creature below them in the darkness and the Tenuk was able to avoid a collision but only just.
"Is that the gigantic, terrifying monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel frowned. He tried to shoot at the second beast, but missed and immediately reloaded.
The Tenuk did not answer. He was too busy concentrating on the flight in the direction of the Nyssi and the Thassalin, even if the other beast was pursuing them. The Kayel had turned unpleasantly to have the monster in front of him. That it was pursuing them was an advantage for the Kayel, so he could aim better and shoot. Two shots hit the beast's upper wings. It screamed in pain and sank below the trees. The Kayel was not sure if it was still pursuing them, but it was certainly not keeping up with them.
A good distance in front of them, Nyssi was hitting with desperation and all her might, while Thassalin was circling around it and spitting flames at the black monster. The creature was definitely burned. It seemed to be incredibly enraged, but not ready to give up. The fireballs did not seem to have the desired effect. When Thassalin paused, Nyssi took the opportunity to grab her own weapon, a good, old rifle. Even if it wasn't made for such purposes, maybe the bullets could at least stun the black beast?
No, it didn't seem so. The creature snorted at me and tried to fly directly towards Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin was agile enough, despite his size, and dodged, but Nyssi let out a scream when she would have lost her balance on Thassalin's smooth scales by a hair's breadth.
"HOW ARE WE GOING TO KILL HER?", Nyssi shrieked.
"LOOK AT YOUR HEADS!"
"THAT WILL BE SERIOUS!"
The Thassalin snorted and then drew a circle, closer to the summit, which he called his home. The dark beast followed, but was easily panicked when a ray of fire touched it from behind. It hadn't realized that it was no longer alone. It panicked even more when the Thassalin came closer and pushed its tail against its head, pushing it off its path.
Muttering and grumbling, and she flew up into the air. With a single glance, everything became dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky, replacing it with a level of eternal night.
When Thassalin could no longer fly, he tried to save himself. He felt how he scraped against the crowns of the trees, before he finally fell into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where Thassalin had fallen and went directly in his direction, so that it pulled with the black level.
"Kayel!", shouted Tenuk, as he slipped out of the fog and began to make noises, to find and greet Nyssi and Thassalin in the dark. "What else should we do now? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
And Nyssi was tired of standing. She was sure she had broken something, but her curious supernatural healing powers were already beginning to work. For Thassalin, unfortunately, that didn't apply. He was still leaning against the only plant that had not been crushed under his weight. Nyssi had tried very hard to get closer to Thassalin, but she could barely see more than two meters in front of her. Everything was darkness and hidden in huge shadows. And in that shadow something was growing and rustling.
A terrible tail, armoured and scaly, thrashed on the ground near Nyssi and had spikes around it. She had, however, felt that the tail was hitting only like a wild animal in all directions, without trying to touch her. The beast, what little Nyssi saw or heard of it, growled and tried to reach with its claws the shadows it had created. Something moved quickly through the darkness, irritating the monster.
All of a sudden, a shot from the rifle pierced the monster's body and it became silent, falling to the ground and remaining there motionless. The darkness around them disappeared and they saw what had happened. On the beast stood the completely stunned Kayel, holding his rifle in his hand.
"That was... the most spectacular shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel gasped for air. His eyes were burning black and a dark energy had enveloped his body. But while he was still gasping, the warmth returned to his armor and his eyes regained their usual yellow color.
And it took me a moment until Nyssi understood what had happened. They all knew that Kayel commanded those particular shadow forces. He rarely used them, because they disturbed and frightened many. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could also use those forces in any kind of darkness. And how Kayel behaved, he also seemed very surprised.
"And is everything in order with you?", Nyssi asked him about that.
"Yes, with me everything is okay. I'll kill something, then everything will be good again." Kayel contemplated his work, while Tenuk flew down, landed next to him and transformed back into his normal form of a sparrow.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its skin was black as ash and smooth, but the slime stuck to its body. The creature had four wings and four limbs that all ended in long, slender claws, and two pointed horns protruded from its head.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could learn what kind of devil they had in front of them, they heard something rustle and jump out of a nearby bush. That creature, however, did not reach them, because a familiar vehicle jumped from the side into it, so that the monster slid along and stopped in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi had to risk it. She grabbed her rifle, jumped without hesitation onto its head and the creature was dead on the spot.
"Oops...", the Retvik mumbled to himself, before he reluctantly turned off the engine and got out of the truck. "Ehm, this wasn't actually supposed to happen. Is everything alright with all of you?"
"You missed the whole action," said Tenuk. "Where were you again?"
"You just called me. I came as fast as possible...", the Retvik sighed. "May I ask what horrible beasts these are?"
Clearly, Thassalin, who had been on his feet again, was able to answer Retvik's question. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit confused, but not seriously injured.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTIOUS MONSTERS. CREATURES THAT HAVE GONE AWAY FROM HERE, WHEN CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible creature that we... helped to kill?", stammered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. COME ON, GIVE ME MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT HIM IN THE HEAD. I HAVE NO FIREARM. TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, ISN'T IT? Thassalin limped towards Kayel and spat on his head. "THANK YOU VERY MUCH, PINTGET. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. I THINK YOU ARE NOT AS TERRIBLE AND NOT AS CAPABLE OF KILLING ENTIRE UNIVERSES."
"Ehm... thanks... I think... Kayel pulled the curtains." "Peia, are we stuck here?"
Nyssi shrugged her shoulders. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the animals that were now definitely dead. Then she took out her favorite weapon, the dagger adorned with the God of the Dead, and began to saw off one of the animal's horns. Afterwards she went to the second one. Just as Nyssi was finished, the animals suddenly went up in flames and turned into a pile of ashes in seconds. The same happened with the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
Also, that is now practical and unpractical at the same time..., sighed Nyssi. "But I will at least send you the photos, I hope."
